<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900425-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>900425-0033.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>04/25/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   MICHAEL MILKEN PLEADED guilty to six felony counts, asexpected, capping a three-year probe of securities fraud andother crimes by Drexel's former junk bond chief. Milken, oncethe world's most-powerful financier, also agreed to pay $600million in fines and restitution and to cooperate with thecontinuing federal inquiry. He will be sentenced Oct. 1 andfaces up to 28 years in prison.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Sears Roebuck's profit plunged 59% in the first quarterdue to &quot;unsatisfactory&quot; results in its core retail businessand hefty claims at its Allstate insurance unit. Sears stockslid $1.125, to $35.375, a 52-week low.   ---   IBM will introduce several low-cost home computers thissummer, making a fresh assault on a market where it has donepoorly in the past.   ---   RJR Nabisco posted a $222 million loss for the firstquarter, reflecting huge debt costs. But the food and tobaccogiant showed strong gains in operating earnings and cashflow.   ---   Western Union said it will file a recapitalization planinvolving an exchange offer of new secured debt and commonstock. The company is trying to avoid a Chapter 11 filing.   ---   Durable goods orders surged 6.7% in March, prompting someanalysts to suggest manufacturing may be rebounding. Therise, reflecting a jump in transporation-equipment orders,was the biggest in more than a year.                                                                                                          Sales of U.S.-built cars and trucks plunged 17.7% inmid-April, a poor performance in what is usually the heart ofthe spring selling season.   ---   The film industry and other producers of copyrightedmaterial were dealt a blow by the Supreme Court, which ruledthe re-release of &quot;Rear Window&quot; violated copyright law.   ---   Quaker Oats decided to spin off its troubled Fisher-Pricetoy business, allowing management to focus on problems in itsfoods business.   ---   Salomon and Morgan Stanley had stronger quarterly results,mainly due to bond-trading windfalls. But the securitiesfirms didn't escape the weakness in investment banking.   ---   Ames Department Stores stocks and bonds tumbled furtheramid growing speculation the chain may seek Chapter 11protection.   ---   The nation's mortgage lenders were accused by seven statesof violating federal law by requiring homeowners to placemore money than necessary in escrow accounts.   ---   Short interest fell 1.3% among major OTC stocks for themonth ended April 12, while borrowed shares in smaller issuesrose 28.3%.   ---   Five oil companies posted mixed quarterly results thatreflected one-time items and higher crude prices.   ---   Labor costs rose 1.6% in the first quarter, fueled byhigher Social Security taxes and other benefits. Costs rose1.1% in the previous quarter.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 137,360,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2654.50, off 12.17; transportation 1134.07, off 7.29;utilities 206.05, up 0.38.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3233.55, up1.32.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.65, off 0.52;spot index 135.54, up 0.20.   Dollar: 158.93 yen, up 1.33; 1.6980 marks, off 0.0015.</TEXT></DOC>